%N A006777 Number of n-step spirals on hexagonal lattice.
%C A006777 The hexagonal lattice is the familiar 2-dimensional lattice in which each point has 6 neighbors. This is sometimes called the triangular lattice.
%C A006777 Corresponds to the Model II single spiral of Table 3 in Szekeres and Guttmann. In Model II every step of the walk consists of either continuing in the current direction or turning clockwise by 60 degrees (i.e., giving an obtuse angle on the path). Roughly speaking, a "single spiral" is a self-avoiding clockwise walk that cannot get stuck in a dead end. More precisely, let u(i) denote the length of the successive straight-line segment of the walk with u(0)=0. Then a walk with k straight line segments (note k <= n), is a single spiral if u(i-4) + u(i-3) < u(i-1) + u(i) for 4 <= i <= k. - _Sean A. Irvine_, Apr 05 2022
